            <td cellpadding="5"> <span editable="true" id="Pagetext"><font style="color: rgb(55, 223, 0);" color="#ffff00"><font size="5">Welcome to my
website.</font></font>
            <p>These pages contain information on my research
interests, my CV and contact information, plus whatever else seems like
a good idea at the time. You can use the links on the left side of the
page to navigate around this site, as well as accessing the University
of Oxford sites.</p>

            <p>I am a post-doctoral research assistant in the <a href="http://www-atm.physics.ox.ac.uk/group/eodg">Earth
Observation Data Group</a> (EODG) in the Sub-Department of <a href="http://www-atm.physics.ox.ac.uk/">Atmospheric, Oceanic
and Planetary Physics</a> at the <a href="http://www.ox.ac.uk/">University of Oxford</a>.
I work with <a href="http://www-atm.physics.ox.ac.uk/group/eodg/eodg_people.html">Don
Grainger</a> on the retrieval of atmospheric aerosol properties
from satellite instruments, along with <a href="http://www-atm.physics.ox.ac.uk/group/eodg/eodg_people.html">Elisa
Carboni, Andy Sayer and Elies Campmany</a>. I believe that the
measurement of atmospheric aerosols on a global scale is one of the
most important and challenging fields of atmospheric research. Aerosols
(a term that encompasses any small solid or liquid particle suspended
in the air) are a very important constituent of our atmosphere, but
their properties, distribution and atmospheric impacts remain
relatively poorly understood. Indeed the last Assessment Report from
the International Panel on Climate Change ( <a href="http://www.ipcc.ch/pub/reports.htm">IPCC 2001</a>)
identified aerosols as the atmospheric constituent with the least well
defined, but potentially biggest, impact on the climate system. For a
more complete description of this work and my previous research, see my
            <a href="research.html">research page</a>.</p>

            <p>I was born and brought up in New Zealand, spending
most of my childhood in the small seaside town of <a href="http://www.whakatane.com/">Whakatane</a> in the
Bay of Plenty (that's the big bay about 2/3 of the way up the Eastern
Coast of the North Island, if you're interested). I gained my tertiary
education in the <a href="http://www.phys.canterbury.ac.nz/">Department
of Physics and Astronomy</a> at the <a href="http://www.canterbury.ac.nz/">Unversity of Canterbury</a>
in Christchurch (about 1/2 way down the East Coast of the South Island
of New Zealand) and gained a PhD in in 2003. My doctoral work involved
the design and testing of an aerosol optical particle counter which
would allow measurement of the refractive index of aerosol particles
(as well as their size and concentration) - &nbsp;something which
no other current instrument is capable of. I am still involved in
efforts (lead by <a href="http://www-atm.physics.ox.ac.uk/group/eodg/eodg_people.html">Dan
Peters</a>) to further develop this instrument.</p>

